## {{lb|en|software engineering}} The act or process of making a product suitable for use in a particular country or region.
# The [[state]] of being [[localized]].
# {{lb|en|algebra}} A [[systematic]] [[method]] of [[add]]ing [[multiplicative inverse]]s to a [[ring]].
# {{lb|en|algebra}} A [[ring of fractions]] of a given ring, such that the complement of the set of allowed [[denominator]]s is an [[ideal]]. 
#* {{quote-web|en|year=2007|author=Ivan Fesenko|site=G13ALS Algebra 2, 2007/2008 @ maths.nottingham.ac.uk|url=https://www.maths.nottingham.ac.uk/plp/pmzibf/als3/leno.pdf|title=Rings and modules|text=&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;3) Geometric interpretation of the '''localization'''.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Let ''V'' be an irreducible algebraic variety. Then ''P'' = ''J''(''V'') is a prime ideal of <math>\mathbb{C}[X_1, . . . , X_n]</math> and so <math>\mathbb{C}[V] = \mathbb{C}[X_1, . . . , X_n]/J(V)</math> is an integral domain.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The '''localization''' <math>\mathbb{C}[X_1, ...,X_n]_P</math> is a subring of <math>\mathbb{C}(X_1, ...,X_n)</math> consisting of rational functions <math>\{f/g : f,g \in \mathbb{C}[X_1, ...,X_n],g \notin P\}</math> which are defined on a nonempty subset of ''V''. If ''V'' = {''x''} is a point, then ''P'' is maximal and <math>\mathbb{C}[X_1, ...,X_n]_P = \{f/g : f, g \in \mathbb{C}[X_1, . . . , X_n], g(x) \ne 0\}</math> consists of rational functions which are defined at ''x''.|page=27}}

